{
  "response": "# Real-Time Notification Panel Accessibility Design Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** Use a11y-planner protocol. Review with a11y-critic after implementation.  \n> **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA  \n> **Users who need accessibility:** Screen reader users, keyboard-only users, low vision users, clinicians using high pressure workflows  \n> **Assistive technologies:** NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver, keyboard-only navigation  \n> **Planned file path:** `docs/a11y-plans/2026-06-12-real-time-notification-panel-a11y-plan.md`\n\n**Feature:** A real-time hospital EHR notification panel with priority-tiered announcements, dismissible notifications, unread badge updates, auto-dismiss behavior, and notification history.  \n**Risk Level:** High  \n**Component/Page Type:** Real-time status system, disclosure/panel, drawer, notification list, live regions, timed content\n\n---\n\n## Scope & Context\n\nThis feature presents live clinical notifications in a React TypeScript EHR application. Notifications arrive through WebSocket while clinicians may be documenting, reviewing orders, or performing other time-sensitive work.\n\nThis is safety-critical. A missed Critical notification is not just an accessibility defect; it can become a patient safety failure. The accessibility design must distinguish between:\n\n- **Critical/Error:** must interrupt immediately.\n- **Warning:** should announce but must not interrupt current work.\n- **Info:** low priority; should not interrupt and should avoid announcement spam.\n\nThe existing implementation is wrong because it uses `<div role=\"alert\">` for every notification tier. `role=\"alert\"` has implicit assertive live region behavior, equivalent to urgent interruption. That is appropriate for Critical notifications but inappropriate for Warning and Info notifications. It causes lower-priority updates to interrupt screen reader users\u2019 current task, violating the priority model of the clinical workflow.\n\nThis plan does **not** claim that live regions alone guarantee every assistive technology will interrupt identically. Screen readers vary in queueing and interruption behavior. This plan does claim that the implementation will use the correct semantic priority model required by WCAG 4.1.3 and the practical behavior expected by NVDA, JAWS, and VoiceOver.\n\nPrimary WCAG criteria:\n\n- **WCAG 4.1.3 Status Messages:** status updates must be programmatically determinable without moving focus.\n- **WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value:** controls and states must expose accessible names, roles, and current values.\n- **WCAG 2.1.1 Keyboard:** all dismiss, open, close, pause, and history interactions must work by keyboard.\n- **WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order:** focus must move predictably when the panel, drawer, or dismissed items change.\n- **WCAG 2.2.1 Timing Adjustable:** auto-dismiss behavior must be pausable or adjustable.\n- **WCAG 1.4.1 Use of Color:** priority tiers cannot rely on red, amber, or blue alone.\n- **WCAG 1.4.3 Contrast Minimum** and **1.4.11 Non-text Contrast:** text, icons, borders, and focus indicators must meet contrast requirements.\n\n---\n\n## Semantic Structure Plan\n\nThe notification system should be part of the application shell, near the top navigation, but its live announcers must be persistent in the DOM and independent from the visible notification list.\n\n### Structure Diagram\n\n```html\n<header>\n  <nav aria-label=\"Primary navigation\">\n    <button aria-label=\"Notifications, 5 unread\" aria-expanded=\"false\" aria-controls=\"notification-panel\">\n      Bell icon\n      <span aria-hidden=\"true\">5</span>\n    </button>\n  </nav>\n</header>\n\n<main id=\"main-content\">\n  Application content\n</main>\n\n<div id=\"critical-announcer\" class=\"sr-only\" aria-live=\"assertive\" aria-atomic=\"true\"></div>\n<div id=\"warning-announcer\" class=\"sr-only\" aria-live=\"polite\" aria-atomic=\"true\"></div>\n<div id=\"info-announcer\" class=\"sr-only\" aria-live=\"polite\" aria-relevant=\"additions\"></div>\n\n<section id=\"notification-panel\" aria-label=\"Notifications\" hidden>\n  <h2>Notifications</h2>\n  <button>Pause auto-dismiss</button>\n  <ul>\n    <li>\n      Notification content\n      <button>Dismiss: Critical lab result \u2014 Patient Doe, John</button>\n    </li>\n  </ul>\n  <button aria-expanded=\"false\" aria-controls=\"notification-history\">Notification history</button>\n</section>\n\n<aside id=\"notification-history\" aria-label=\"Notification history\" aria-live=\"off\" hidden>\n  <h2>Notification history</h2>\n  <button>Close notification history</button>\n  <ol>\n    <li>Historical notification</li>\n  </ol>\n</aside>\n```\n\nSemantic decisions:\n\n- The bell control is a native `<button>`, not a generic element, satisfying WCAG 2.1.1 and 4.1.2.\n- The notification panel is a named `section`, satisfying WCAG 1.3.1 and 2.4.6.\n- Notifications are a list because the visible panel contains a collection of related items, satisfying WCAG 1.3.1.\n- Notification history is an `aside` or named `section` with `aria-live=\"off\"` because it is browseable historical content, not a live announcement surface. This satisfies WCAG 1.3.1 and prevents duplicate announcements under WCAG 4.1.3.\n- Priority icons or symbols must be decorative if text already communicates priority. Use `aria-hidden=\"true\"` for symbols such as `\u00d7`, warning triangles, or colored icons when the accessible text already includes the meaning. WCAG 1.1.1 and 4.1.2.\n\n---\n\n## Interaction Pattern Design\n\n### Interactive Elements Table\n\n| Widget | APG Pattern | Keyboard Model | ARIA Attributes | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Bell notification button | APG Button / Disclosure-style controlling button: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/disclosure/ | Tab focuses. Enter/Space opens or closes panel. Escape closes panel if focus is inside panel. | `aria-label=\"Notifications, N unread\"`, `aria-expanded`, `aria-controls` | 2.1.1, 4.1.2, 2.4.3 |\n| Notification panel | Disclosure/popup region, not modal unless it blocks page interaction | Focus enters panel after open. Tab proceeds through controls. Escape closes and restores focus to bell. | `aria-label=\"Notifications\"` on region; panel referenced by bell `aria-controls` | 1.3.1, 2.4.3, 4.1.2 |\n| Dismiss notification button | APG Button: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/ | Tab focuses. Enter/Space dismisses. | Native button with accessible name: `Dismiss: [priority] \u2014 [short summary]` | 2.1.1, 2.4.6, 4.1.2 |\n| Pause auto-dismiss toggle | APG Toggle Button: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/ | Tab focuses. Enter/Space toggles. | `aria-pressed=\"true/false\"` | 2.1.1, 2.2.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Notification history trigger | APG Button / Disclosure or Dialog depending final UI | Tab focuses. Enter/Space opens history drawer. Escape closes drawer. | `aria-expanded`, `aria-controls` | 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 4.1.2 |\n| Notification history drawer | APG Dialog if overlaying page: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/dialog-modal/; named region if inline drawer | If modal drawer: trap focus. If non-modal drawer: logical tab order through drawer controls. Escape closes. | If modal: `role=\"dialog\"`, `aria-modal=\"true\"`, `aria-labelledby`. Always `aria-live=\"off\"` | 2.1.2, 2.4.3, 4.1.2 |\n| Critical announcer | Live region, not visible widget | No keyboard interaction | `aria-live=\"assertive\"`, `aria-atomic=\"true\"` | 4.1.3 |\n| Warning announcer | Live region, not visible widget | No keyboard interaction | `aria-live=\"polite\"`, `aria-atomic=\"true\"` | 4.1.3 |\n| Info announcer | Live region, not visible widget | No keyboard interaction | `aria-live=\"polite\"`, `aria-relevant=\"additions\"` | 4.1.3 |\n\n### Live Region Architecture\n\nUse three persistent, visually hidden announcer elements mounted once at app shell level:\n\n```html\n<div id=\"critical-announcer\" aria-live=\"assertive\" aria-atomic=\"true\" class=\"sr-only\"></div>\n<div id=\"warning-announcer\" aria-live=\"polite\" aria-atomic=\"true\" class=\"sr-only\"></div>\n<div id=\"info-announcer\" aria-live=\"polite\" aria-relevant=\"additions\" class=\"sr-only\"></div>\n```\n\nDo not append the visible notification cards into these live regions. Instead, inject a plain announcement string into the appropriate announcer. Use a clear-then-inject pattern:\n\n1. Clear the live region text.\n2. Wait for the DOM update cycle.\n3. Inject the new announcement text.\n\nThis reduces race conditions where NVDA or JAWS miss DOM additions because the live region was created or populated in the same render pass.\n\nPriority behavior:\n\n- **Critical:** assertive, atomic. Full message must be read because partial clinical information is dangerous. Example announcement: \u201cCritical notification. Critical lab result: Patient Doe, John. Potassium 6.8 mEq/L. Requires immediate review.\u201d\n- **Warning:** polite, atomic. The full warning should be understood, but it must not interrupt current screen reader speech. Example: \u201cWarning notification. Medication order pending countersignature: Lisinopril 10 milligrams, Patient Chen, Sarah.\u201d\n- **Info:** polite, additions only. Info should avoid re-reading previous content. Example: \u201cInfo notification. Appointment reminder: Team huddle at 14:00.\u201d\n\n`role=\"status\"` may be used for low-priority general status messages because it maps to polite behavior. It is appropriate for non-urgent status like \u201cNotifications paused\u201d or \u201c3 notifications dismissed.\u201d It is not appropriate for Critical clinical alerts.\n\n`role=\"alert\"` may be used only for Critical-equivalent urgent alerts, but this plan prefers explicit `aria-live=\"assertive\"` on the dedicated Critical announcer for clarity and tier separation. Do not use `role=\"alert\"` on every visible notification card.\n\n---\n\n## Focus Management Plan\n\n### Bell and Panel\n\nWhen the bell button opens the panel:\n\n1. Save the bell button as the return-focus target.\n2. Set `aria-expanded=\"true\"` on the bell.\n3. Move focus to the panel heading if the panel is primarily informational, or to the first actionable control if immediate action is expected. For this panel, focus should move to the first control inside the panel: usually \u201cPause auto-dismiss,\u201d followed by the newest notification dismiss button. This keeps keyboard users in the newly opened interface. WCAG 2.4.3.\n4. Escape closes the panel and restores focus to the bell button. WCAG 2.1.1 and 2.4.3.\n\nIf the panel is non-modal, focus should not be trapped. If the visual design overlays content and prevents interaction with the page behind it, it must use the APG Modal Dialog pattern with focus trap and `aria-modal=\"true\"`.\n\n### New Notifications While Panel Is Closed\n\nDo not move focus when notifications arrive. Live region announcements communicate the update without stealing the clinician\u2019s position in the EHR. WCAG 4.1.3.\n\n### New Notifications While Panel Is Open\n\nDo not automatically move focus to the new notification. Add it to the top of the list visually and programmatically. Announce through the appropriate live region. Moving focus on every WebSocket event would disrupt keyboard and screen reader users. WCAG 2.4.3.\n\n### Dismiss Focus Behavior\n\nWhen a notification is dismissed by keyboard or pointer:\n\n- If there is a next notification in the list, move focus to that notification\u2019s dismiss button.\n- If the dismissed item was the last visible notification but a previous item remains, move focus to the nearest remaining dismiss button.\n- If no notifications remain, move focus to the bell button if the panel closes automatically, or to the empty-state message container with `tabindex=\"-1\"` if the panel remains open.\n- Critical notifications should require explicit dismissal and should never auto-dismiss.\n\nThis prevents focus loss after DOM removal. WCAG 2.4.3.\n\n### History Drawer\n\nWhen history opens:\n\n1. Set the history trigger `aria-expanded=\"true\"`.\n2. If the drawer overlays or blocks the page, implement APG Modal Dialog with focus trap, Escape close, and focus restoration to the history trigger.\n3. If the drawer is inline, move focus to the drawer heading with `tabindex=\"-1\"` or to the first history item if the requirement is to review the newest event immediately.\n4. Scroll to the latest history item on open, but ensure focus also moves to the corresponding semantic target. Scroll without focus is insufficient in an SPA. WCAG 2.4.3.\n5. History must use `aria-live=\"off\"` so old items are not re-announced as new status messages. WCAG 4.1.3.\n\n---\n\n## State Communication Design\n\n### State Communication Table\n\n| State | Visual Indicator | Programmatic Indicator | ARIA Attribute | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Panel closed | Bell only, unread badge visible | Bell reports collapsed state | `aria-expanded=\"false\"` | 4.1.2 |\n| Panel open | Panel visible | Bell reports expanded state | `aria-expanded=\"true\"` | 4.1.2 |\n| Unread count | Badge text, capped at `99+` | Bell accessible name includes count | `aria-label=\"Notifications, 5 unread\"` | 4.1.2, 4.1.3 |\n| Critical notification | Red styling, critical icon, \u201cCritical\u201d text | Assertive announcer receives full message | `aria-live=\"assertive\"`, `aria-atomic=\"true\"` | 4.1.3 |\n| Warning notification | Amber styling, warning icon, \u201cWarning\u201d text | Polite announcer receives full message | `aria-live=\"polite\"`, `aria-atomic=\"true\"` | 4.1.3 |\n| Info notification | Blue styling, info icon, \u201cInfo\u201d text | Polite announcer receives new item text | `aria-live=\"polite\"`, `aria-relevant=\"additions\"` | 4.1.3 |\n| Auto-dismiss enabled | Timer/progress text, pause button unpressed | Toggle exposes unpressed state | `aria-pressed=\"false\"` | 2.2.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Auto-dismiss paused | \u201cAuto-dismiss paused\u201d text | Toggle exposes pressed state; polite status message | `aria-pressed=\"true\"`, optional `role=\"status\"` | 2.2.1, 4.1.2, 4.1.3 |\n| Notification dismissed | Item removed, optional status text | Focus moves predictably; optional polite status | `role=\"status\"` for summary only | 2.4.3, 4.1.3 |\n| History open | Drawer visible | Trigger expanded; drawer named | `aria-expanded=\"true\"`, `aria-label` or `aria-labelledby` | 1.3.1, 4.1.2 |\n| History closed | Drawer hidden | Trigger collapsed | `aria-expanded=\"false\"` | 4.1.2 |\n| Disabled controls | Muted visual style plus text if needed | Native `disabled` for real buttons | `disabled`, not only `aria-disabled` | 4.1.2 |\n\n### Badge Count Strategy\n\nThe badge should not have its own live region that announces every increment. That would spam screen reader users with \u201c3, 4, 5\u201d during bursts.\n\nUse this strategy:\n\n- The bell button accessible name always reflects the current count: `Notifications, 5 unread`.\n- The visible badge is `aria-hidden=\"true\"` because the accessible name already includes the count.\n- Announce new incoming notifications through the priority announcers, not through badge changes.\n- When multiple low-priority notifications arrive rapidly, batch Warning and Info announcements where clinically acceptable, for example: \u201c3 new informational notifications.\u201d Do not batch Critical notifications in a way that hides individual critical content.\n- Only announce badge summary when the panel is closed and a new notification arrives. When the panel is open, users can perceive new items in context through the list and live region message.\n\nThis satisfies WCAG 4.1.3 while avoiding announcement overload.\n\n---\n\n## Auto-Dismiss Timing Plan\n\nCurrent timeouts:\n\n- Critical: never auto-dismiss. Correct for safety and WCAG 2.2.1.\n- Warning: 30 seconds. Borderline; acceptable only if auto-dismiss can be paused.\n- Info: 10 seconds. Too short for many screen reader, magnification, cognitive, and keyboard-only users unless pause/stop/hide control exists.\n\nRequired design:\n\n1. Provide a persistent \u201cPause auto-dismiss\u201d toggle in the notification panel.\n2. Respect the pause setting for Warning and Info notifications.\n3. Critical notifications never auto-dismiss.\n4. When auto-dismiss is active, visible notifications should show remaining time using text, not only animation or color.\n5. Do not announce countdown ticks through live regions. That would create noise.\n6. If an Info notification receives keyboard focus or pointer hover, pause its auto-dismiss while focused or hovered.\n7. When a notification auto-dismisses, do not move focus unless focus was inside that notification. If focus was inside it, move focus using the dismiss focus rules above.\n\nWCAG citation: **2.2.1 Timing Adjustable** requires users to turn off, adjust, or extend time limits unless an exception applies. No exception should be assumed in an EHR notification panel.\n\n---\n\n## Visual Accessibility Plan\n\nPriority tier colors must not be the only differentiator.\n\n- Critical: red border/background accent + \u201cCritical\u201d text + critical icon.\n- Warning: amber accent + \u201cWarning\u201d text + warning icon.\n- Info: blue accent + \u201cInfo\u201d text + info icon.\n\nContrast requirements:\n\n- Notification text: 4.5:1 minimum. WCAG 1.4.3.\n- Large priority labels: 3:1 minimum if genuinely large text. WCAG 1.4.3.\n- Buttons, badge outline, icons, focus indicators: 3:1 minimum against adjacent colors. WCAG 1.4.11.\n- Focus indicator: use a two-color visible focus ring with at least 3:1 contrast and sufficient area. WCAG 2.4.7 and 2.4.13.\n- Dismiss and bell controls: minimum 24x24 CSS pixels under WCAG 2.5.8; 44x44 recommended for clinical speed and touch use.\n- The `\u00d7` symbol inside dismiss buttons must be `aria-hidden=\"true\"` if present, while the button accessible name carries the actual action. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- Motion for notification entry/exit must respect `prefers-reduced-motion`. WCAG 2.3.3.\n- At 200% zoom and 320px equivalent width, the panel must reflow without horizontal scrolling. WCAG 1.4.10.\n- Sticky headers must not obscure focused controls in the panel or drawer. WCAG 2.4.11.\n\n---\n\n## Content Accessibility Plan\n\nNotification text must be clinically clear and screen-reader-friendly.\n\nAccessible notification message format:\n\n- Start with priority: \u201cCritical notification.\u201d\n- State the clinical event.\n- Include patient name only as required by the EHR context.\n- Include the required action if available.\n- Avoid relying on punctuation pauses alone.\n\nExample Critical live message:\n\n\u201cCritical notification. Critical lab result: Patient Doe, John. Potassium 6.8 milliequivalents per liter. Requires immediate review.\u201d\n\nDismiss button label pattern:\n\n- `Dismiss: Critical lab result \u2014 Patient Doe, John`\n- `Dismiss: Medication order pending countersignature \u2014 Patient Chen, Sarah`\n- `Dismiss: Appointment reminder \u2014 Team huddle at 14:00`\n\nDo not use `title` as the accessible name. Use visible text, `aria-label`, or `aria-labelledby`. WCAG 2.4.6 and 4.1.2.\n\nHistory items should include timestamp, priority, message, and read/dismissed status in text. Do not communicate read/unread status only with font weight or color. WCAG 1.4.1.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Automated and DOM Verification\n\nRun axe-core against these states:\n\n- No notifications.\n- Panel closed with unread badge.\n- Panel open with Critical, Warning, and Info notifications.\n- Auto-dismiss paused and unpaused.\n- History drawer open.\n- Empty notification state.\n- Badge count over 99.\n\nDOM verification is required:\n\n- Confirm three announcer nodes exist persistently at app shell level.\n- Confirm Critical announcer has `aria-live=\"assertive\"` and `aria-atomic=\"true\"`.\n- Confirm Warning announcer has `aria-live=\"polite\"` and `aria-atomic=\"true\"`.\n- Confirm Info announcer has `aria-live=\"polite\"` and `aria-relevant=\"additions\"`.\n- Confirm visible notification cards do not all use `role=\"alert\"`.\n- Confirm dismiss controls are native `<button>` elements.\n- Confirm bell accessible name includes unread count.\n- Confirm history has `aria-live=\"off\"`.\n\n### Keyboard Tests\n\n- Tab to bell button.\n- Press Enter/Space: panel opens.\n- Focus moves into panel.\n- Tab through pause toggle, notifications, dismiss buttons, history trigger.\n- Press Escape: panel closes and focus returns to bell.\n- Dismiss first notification: focus moves to next notification dismiss button.\n- Dismiss last notification: focus moves to bell or empty-state target according to final UI behavior.\n- Open history: focus moves to history heading or first item.\n- Close history: focus returns to history trigger.\n- Pause auto-dismiss toggle works with Enter and Space.\n\n### Screen Reader Tests\n\nNVDA:\n\n- Trigger Critical while reading another part of the app. Expected: Critical announcement interrupts.\n- Trigger Warning while reading. Expected: queued polite announcement, no interruption.\n- Trigger Info burst. Expected: no repeated badge count spam; Info messages are polite and limited.\n- Open bell. Expected: button announces \u201cNotifications, N unread, button, expanded/collapsed.\u201d\n- Dismiss notification. Expected: next focus target is announced.\n\nJAWS:\n\n- Confirm Warning and Info do not behave like alerts.\n- Confirm clear-then-inject announcer pattern reliably announces new messages.\n- Confirm `aria-atomic` causes full Critical and Warning messages to be read.\n\nVoiceOver macOS:\n\n- Confirm bell accessible name includes count.\n- Confirm panel heading and notification list are navigable.\n- Confirm history is not announced as live updates.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n\n- Critical notifications interrupt with full message.\n- Warning notifications announce politely with full message.\n- Info notifications announce politely without re-reading entire notification history.\n- Badge count is available on the bell button and does not spam announcements.\n- Dismiss buttons are keyboard accessible native buttons with specific names.\n- Auto-dismiss can be paused.\n- Focus never disappears after notification removal.\n- History drawer is navigable and is not a live region.\n- No lower-priority notification uses `role=\"alert\"`.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Tasks\n\n### Task 1: Live Region Architecture\n\n**Files:**\n\n- App shell notification provider/component\n- Notification announcer utility\n- Notification tests\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<div id=\"critical-announcer\" aria-live=\"assertive\" aria-atomic=\"true\" class=\"sr-only\"></div>\n<div id=\"warning-announcer\" aria-live=\"polite\" aria-atomic=\"true\" class=\"sr-only\"></div>\n<div id=\"info-announcer\" aria-live=\"polite\" aria-relevant=\"additions\" class=\"sr-only\"></div>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `aria-live=\"assertive\"` for Critical: WCAG 4.1.3.\n- `aria-live=\"polite\"` for Warning and Info: WCAG 4.1.3.\n- `aria-atomic=\"true\"` for Critical and Warning: WCAG 4.1.3.\n- `aria-relevant=\"additions\"` for Info: WCAG 4.1.3.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Critical injects into Critical announcer only.\n- Warning injects into Warning announcer only.\n- Info injects into Info announcer only.\n- Visible notification cards are not used as live region announcers.\n\n**Review checkpoint:** Verify priority-tier live region separation and no blanket `role=\"alert\"` usage.\n\n### Task 2: Bell Button and Badge Count\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `aria-label=\"Notifications, N unread\"`: WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-expanded`: WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-controls`: WCAG 4.1.2.\n- Badge text `aria-hidden=\"true\"` if count is already in button name.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- Enter/Space opens panel.\n- Escape closes panel when focus is inside.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Count `99+` is visual; accessible name should remain meaningful, such as \u201cNotifications, 99 or more unread.\u201d\n- Badge updates do not create standalone live region spam.\n\n**Review checkpoint:** Verify accessible name strategy and announcement throttling.\n\n### Task 3: Notification Panel and Dismiss Buttons\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<section id=\"notification-panel\" aria-label=\"Notifications\">\n  <h2>Notifications</h2>\n  <button aria-pressed=\"false\">Pause auto-dismiss</button>\n  <ul>\n    <li>\n      <p>Critical notification...</p>\n      <button>Dismiss: Critical lab result \u2014 Patient Doe, John</button>\n    </li>\n  </ul>\n</section>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `aria-pressed` for pause toggle: WCAG 4.1.2 and 2.2.1.\n- Native buttons for dismiss: WCAG 2.1.1 and 4.1.2.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Dismiss with Enter and Space.\n- Focus moves to next dismiss button.\n- Last dismiss does not drop focus to `body`.\n\n**Review checkpoint:** Verify keyboard support and focus-after-removal behavior.\n\n### Task 4: Auto-Dismiss Controls\n\n**Requirements:**\n\n- Critical never auto-dismisses.\n- Warning and Info pause when global pause is active.\n- Focused or hovered notifications do not auto-dismiss.\n- No live countdown announcements.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Info does not disappear while focused.\n- Pause toggle prevents Warning and Info removal.\n- Auto-dismiss removal preserves focus.\n\n**Review checkpoint:** Verify WCAG 2.2.1 compliance.\n\n### Task 5: Notification History Drawer\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<aside id=\"notification-history\" aria-label=\"Notification history\" aria-live=\"off\">\n  <h2>Notification history</h2>\n  <button>Close notification history</button>\n  <ol>\n    <li>Timestamp, priority, message, read status</li>\n  </ol>\n</aside>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `aria-live=\"off\"`: prevents historical content from being treated as new status. WCAG 4.1.3.\n- If modal drawer: `role=\"dialog\"`, `aria-modal=\"true\"`, `aria-labelledby`: WCAG 4.1.2.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Opening history moves focus into drawer.\n- Latest item is scrolled into view and reachable.\n- Closing restores focus to history trigger.\n- History items are not announced as new live notifications.\n\n**Review checkpoint:** Verify region semantics, focus management, and live-off behavior.\n\n---\n\n## a11y-Critic Review Checkpoints\n\n| Checkpoint | After Task | Focus Areas |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Live regions | Three-tier architecture, no blanket alerts, clear-then-inject behavior |\n| 2 | Bell and badge | Accessible name, count behavior, no badge spam |\n| 3 | Panel and dismiss | Native buttons, keyboard support, focus after dismissal |\n| 4 | Auto-dismiss | WCAG 2.2.1 pause/stop/hide compliance |\n| 5 | History drawer | `aria-live=\"off\"`, focus on open/close, scroll and reading order |\n\n---\n\n## Failure Modes This Plan Prevents\n\n- Warning and Info notifications interrupting clinician workflow because they use `role=\"alert\"`.\n- Screen readers missing WebSocket updates because live regions are created and populated in the same render.\n- Badge count announcing every increment.\n- Dismiss controls being unreachable because they are `<span>` elements.\n- Focus disappearing after a notification is removed from the DOM.\n- Auto-dismissed notifications vanishing before AT users can read them.\n- Notification history being incorrectly treated as new live content.\n- Priority being communicated only by red, amber, or blue color.\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- WAI-ARIA APG Button Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/\n- WAI-ARIA APG Disclosure Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/disclosure/\n- WAI-ARIA APG Modal Dialog Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/dialog-modal/\n- WCAG 2.2 Quick Reference: https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG22/quickref/\n- WCAG 4.1.3 Status Messages\n- WCAG 2.2.1 Timing Adjustable\n- WCAG 2.1.1 Keyboard\n- WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order\n- WCAG 1.4.1 Use of Color\n- WCAG 1.4.3 Contrast Minimum",
